    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-07-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-07-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="92"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d92">
                <head>92. Memorandum From <persName type="from">Dean Moor</persName> of the
                    Operations Staff of the National Security Council to the President’s Assistant
                    for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="to"
                        >Kissinger</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d92fn1">Source:
                        National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential
                        Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 1320, Unfiled
                        Material, 7 of 19. Secret. Sent for information.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1969-07-01">July 1, 1969</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Growing Economic Problems in South Vietnam</item>
                </list>
                <p>During the last few weeks we have been getting an increasing number of reports
                    from a wide variety of sources indicating that the problems of inflation, budget
                    deficit, mismanagement and other economic woes have sharply increased in
                    intensity over the last few months. Already, these problems are beginning to sap
                    some of the Government’s vitality in attempting to build a competitive position
                    against Communists in a future post-war environment.</p>
                <p>The cable at Tab A<note n="2" xml:id="d92fn2">Tab A, telegram 13078 from Saigon,
                        June 28, is attached but not printed.</note> is a rather good summary of the
                    current scene. It sets out the views of an International Monetary Fund expert
                    who made a study of the situation. His views are based on several previous
                        <gloss target="#t_IMF1">IMF</gloss> studies. Following are some of the
                    highlights: <list>
                        <item>—The overall price stability maintained this year has cost the <gloss
                                target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss> some $80,000,000 in reserves. Loss of
                            similar magnitude can be expected during the rest of 1969.</item>
                        <item>—Even so, maintenance of price stability is questionable in view of
                            the recent <gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss> wage increase,
                            probability of extra heavy military expenditures and other
                            factors.</item>
                        <item>—The only solution is a massive new tax program. Both <gloss
                                target="#t_IMF1">IMF</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss>
                            officials, however, believe it impossible for the <gloss
                                target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss> to implement a significant tax
                            program.</item>
                        <pb facs="0319" n="283" xml:id="pg_283"/>
                        <item>—The situation is of such concern to the <gloss target="#t_GVN1"
                                >GVN</gloss> that a shakeup in the economic leadership of the regime
                            is contemplated, but few believe that this will do much good.</item>
                        <item>—The U.S. economic advisors in Saigon generally agree with the <gloss
                                target="#t_IMF1">IMF</gloss> view.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
            </div>
